9 plugging and reclamation based on a third-party engineering
10 estimate, whichever is greater.
11 (C) For a class I captive hazardous waste well, $300,000.00 or
12 the amount sufficient to cover the costs of well plugging and
13 reclamation based on a third-party engineering estimate, whichever
14 is greater.
15 (D) For a class I captive nonhazardous waste well, $150,000.00
16 or the amount sufficient to cover the costs of well plugging and
17 reclamation based on a third-party engineering estimate, whichever
18 is greater.
19 (E) For multiple class I nonhazardous wells, not to exceed 4
20 wells, $500,000.00 for a blanket bond.
21 (F) For a class III well, $100,000.00.
22 (G) For multiple class III wells, not to exceed 20 wells,
23 $1,000,000.00 for a blanket bond.
24 (ii) Is sufficient to cover the costs of well plugging and
25 reclamation, as determined by the department based on engineering,
26 geotechnical, environmental, or location conditions.
27 (b) The terms of the instrument cannot be altered without the
28 approval of the department.
29 (c) A cash account or deposit is held in trust by a federally
TMV S01207'25 (S-2) ei8gfh

57
1 insured financial institution that meets all of the following
2 requirements:
3 (i) Is regulated by banking authorities of this state or the
4 federal government.
5 (ii) Holds the deposit in a segregated trust account solely for
6 the benefit of this state.
7 (iii) Releases funds only upon written authorization from this
8 state.
9 (iv) The deposit cannot be offset against or encumbered by any
10 other obligation.
11 (d) Cancellation of a bond requires at least 120 days' advance
12 notice.
13 (e) The instrument remains in effect until the department
14 determines that all of the following apply:
15 (i) The class I well or class III well has been permanently
16 plugged and abandoned in compliance with law and in a manner that
17 protects underground sources of drinking water.
18 (ii) All contamination at the site has been remediated.
19 (iii) The soil at the site has been stabilized and the site has
20 been regraded to conditions approved by the department, with
21 vegetation sufficiently established to prevent erosion or offsite
22 runoff.
23 (iv) All required well records and supporting documentation
24 have been submitted to the department, no adverse environmental
25 conditions caused by the drilling of the well remain at the surface
26 or within an underground source of drinking water, and the
27 department considers the site to meet plugging-approved status.
28 (3) Payment under an instrument required by subsection (2)
29 does not relieve the operator from any other legal requirements.
TMV S01207'25 (S-2) ei8gfh

58
1 Assets under the instrument revert to the operator's control, at
2 the operator's request, only after the operator has adequately
3 plugged the wells, reclaimed the well site, and complied with all
4 orders of the supervisor or department under this act.
5 (4) The financial responsibility under subsection (1) shall
6 also include environmental pollution insurance coverage that
7 complies with all of the following:
8 (a) The amount of coverage meets both of the following
9 requirements:
10 (i) Is at least $5,000,000.00 per occurrence for a multisource
11 commercial hazardous waste disposal well or $2,500,000.00 per
12 occurrence for a captive hazardous waste disposal well.
13 (ii) Is considered by the department to be sufficient to cover
14 the remediation of private property that could reasonably be
15 affected by future environmental incidents caused by the drilling
16 of the well and the replacement of drinking water supplies for
17 properties with affected water wells.
18 (b) After the well is plugged, the insurance remains in effect
19 until the department determines the well meets plugging-approved
20 status requirements and extends for an additional 10 years for a
21 class I hazardous waste well or 5 years for a class I nonhazardous
22 well.
23 (c) The insurance is provided by an insurance carrier
24 authorized, licensed, or permitted to conduct such insurance
25 business in this state and that holds at least an A- rating by AM
26 Best or any comparable rating service.
27 (d) The insurance is not issued by a captive insurer, surplus
28 line insurer, or risk retention group.
29 (5) Within 2 years after the effective date of the amendatory
TMV S01207'25 (S-2) ei8gfh

59
1 act that added this section and annually thereafter, an operator of
2 a test well shall, for each well, file proof of financial
3 responsibility for which this state is the sole beneficiary. The
4 financial responsibility shall be a surety bond issued by an
5 authorized insurer whose certificate of authority is in good
6 standing, a cash account, or an automatically annually renewing
7 certificate of deposit. The financial responsibility shall comply,
8 and shall be interpreted to comply, with the following, as
9 applicable:
10 (a) The amount meets both of the following requirements:
11 (i) Is at least $10,000.00.
12 (ii) Is sufficient to cover the costs of well plugging and
13 reclamation, as determined by the department based on engineering,
14 geotechnical, environmental, or location conditions.
15 (b) The terms of the instrument shall not be altered without
16 the approval of the department.
17 (c) A cash account or deposit is held in trust by a federally
18 insured financial institution that meets all of the following
19 requirements:
20 (i) Is regulated by banking authorities of this state or the
21 federal government.
22 (ii) Holds the deposit in a segregated trust account solely for
23 the benefit of this state.
24 (iii) Releases funds only upon written authorization from this
25 state.
26 (iv) The deposit cannot be offset against or encumbered by any
27 other obligation.
28 (d) Cancellation of a bond requires at least 120 days' advance
29 notice.
